         <abstract>
            <p>Mr. Gaines concludes that banks in the future should be more cautious in balancing maturities of assets and liabilities. They now know that they can no longer rely upon C/Ds as a source of funds, which makes it more difficult for banks to become aggressive lenders now. He suggests that principal responsibility for encouraging better bank asset/liability management and for stimulating bank lending rests with the Federal Reserve. Inducement might be provided through Fed encouragement of new short-term instruments to replace certificates of deposit. The Fed could adapt changes in existing regulations.</p>
